    "refcode_long": "The Adventist Home, p. 315.2 (Ellen Gould White)",
    "element_type": "p",
    "element_subtype": "standard-indented",
    "content": "The angels look with intense interest upon every family, to see how the children are treated by parents, guardians, or friends. What strange mismanagement they witness in a family where father and mother are at variance! The tones of the voice of father and mother, their looks, their words&mdash;all make it manifest that they are not united in the management of their children. The father casts reflections upon the mother and leads the children to hold in disrespect the mother&apos;s tenderness and affection for the little ones. The mother thinks she is compelled to give large affection to the children, to gratify and indulge them, because she thinks the father is harsh and impatient and she must work to counteract the influence of his severity.<sup class=\"chapterendnote\"><a class=\"chapterendnote\">11<span class=\"chapterendnote\"><span class=\"egwlink egwlink_book\" title=\"RH 3-13-1894\" data-link=\"821.13381\">The Review and Herald, March 13, 1894</span>.</span></a></sup>",
